0":"1068–1130","1070–Female":"1070–Deceased","about 1173":"about 1173","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","1142":"1142","1130":"1130","1173":"1173","1070":"1070","1113":"1113","1068":"1068","1100":"1100","about 1132":"about 1132","about 1100":"about 1100","about 1130":"about 1130","about 1142":"about 1142","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Hanging Marsh, Garth Celyn, Aber Garth Celyn, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Bradenham, Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Bradenham, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Windsor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Windsor (Berkshire), Windsor in Stratford upon Avon (Warwickshire), Winsor in Copythorne (Hampshire), Winsor in Yealmpton (Devon), or Broadwindsor and Little Windsor (Dorset). All these places have the same linguistic origin, whose meaning is controversial, but seems to be ‘windlass bank’ (Old English <i>windels</i> + <i>ōra</i>).","in Yorkshire perhaps a habitational name from Winds Over in Middleton (near Ilkley, Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>wind</i> ‘wind’ (genitive <i>windes</i>) + <i>ofer</i> ‘slope, hill, ridge’."],"variants":[{"name":"Winzer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Ilse, Ingo, Wilhelm.","German: occupational name for a vine-grower or vintner, Middle High German <i>winzer</i>.","German: habitational name from any of various places so named in Bavaria."]},{"name":"Winsor","meanings":["English: variant of   Windsor  . This is the spelling used for places so named in Devon and Hampshire.","Perhaps also an Americanized form of German   Winzer  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Windsor I was born about 1100, in Pembroke, Pembrokeshire, Wales, his father, William FitzWalter, Constable of Windsor, Keeper of Windsor Forest William de Windsor, was 34 and his mother, Agnes de Valognes, was 32. He had at least 2 sons with Gwaladus Verch Rhiwallon. He died about 1173, in Pembrokeshire, Wales, at the age of 75."},"et":{"about 1100–about 1173":"umbes 1100–umbes 1173","1100–1173":"1100–1173","1113–1142":"1113–1142","1132–1176":"1132–1176","1142–Male":"1142–Surnud","1068–1130":"1068–1130","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","about 1173":"umbes 1173","1176":"1176","1132":"1132","